---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="The sun reaches the feet: the December alignment | Chennakesava Swamy, Markapur"
  description="Each winter, dawn light passes through the gopuram at Markapur and falls at the feet of the deity for around twenty minutes. What is known about it, and what is not."
>
  <h1>The sun reaches the feet</h1>
  <p class="page-te">Mid-December into early January</p>

  <div style="position:relative; overflow:hidden; padding:30px 20px; margin-bottom:26px;
              border:1px solid var(--gold-line); background:linear-gradient(to top, var(--gold-glow), transparent 72%)">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 200 200" aria-hidden="true"
         style="position:absolute; bottom:-92px; left:50%; transform:translateX(-50%);
                width:230px; color:var(--gold); opacity:.2; pointer-events:none">
      <use href="#rays" />
    </svg>
    <p class="lead" style="position:relative; margin:0">
      For about twenty minutes at dawn, light enters through an opening in the 135-foot
      gopuram, travels the length of the temple, and comes to rest at the feet of
      Chennakesava Swamy.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Temples across southern India are built to catch the sun on particular days, but few
    do it through a tower of this height, and fewer still are so little documented. The
    alignment at Markapur is mentioned in passing by every account of the temple and
    described carefully by none of them.
  </p>

  <h2>What the sources actually say</h2>
  <p>
    They do not agree. Three different windows are published, and no source explains where
    its dates came from:
  </p>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Reported window</th><th class="num">Length</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>16 December – 4 January</td><td class="num">20 days</td></tr>
        <tr><td>23 December – 3 January</td><td class="num">12 days</td></tr>
        <tr><td>16 December – 14 January</td><td class="num">30 days</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>So this site will not give you a date.</strong> Travelling a long way for a
      twenty-minute event on the strength of a source that might be a month wrong is not
      something we are willing to cause. The overlap common to all three accounts is the
      final week of December, but confirm at the temple before planning around it.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>What would settle it</h2>
  <p>
    One person at the temple, on the right mornings, with a phone camera and the date.
    That is the whole of it. The observation has almost certainly been made a thousand
    times by devotees who had no reason to write it down, and it exists nowhere anyone can
    find it.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you have seen it, the dates and times are worth recording. It is the one thing this
    temple has that no other Chennakesava temple does.
  </p>
</Base>
